Diagnosis. Eyes uniformly pilose (typical of subgenus
Pandasyopthalmus
), covered with dense, white pile as long as pedicel, and narrowly separated by a length of about two ommatidia ( Fig. 7A ). Face with distinct tubercle. Spurious vein extending beyond the meeting point of vein M with the discal cross-vein ( Fig. 2A ). Medial longitu- dinal protuberance at the boundary between sterna 2 and 3 present ( Figs 2 C–D: pr); posterior margin of sternum 4 medially protruded, with two tufts of black pile medially ( Figs 2 C–D: t). Surstylus squared with apical protuberance and inner spine (marked with arrow on Fig. 3B ); hypandrium as in Figs 3 C–D; paramere broad basally and tapering towards the rounded apex, with a lateral spine (marked with arrow on Figs 3 C–D).
